{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":67226,"duration_api_ms":67188,"num_turns":13,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"7465066b-c1e8-4d54-b000-c03dd36efe4c","total_cost_usd":0.35225725,"usage":{"input_tokens":9,"cache_creation_input_tokens":27401,"cache_read_input_tokens":259712,"output_tokens":2044,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":27401,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":9,"outputTokens":2044,"cacheReadInputTokens":259712,"cacheCreationInputTokens":27401,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.35225725,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Both amendments identify real gaps in the current implementation. Amendment fr-5-f1c7b7b6 correctly identifies that legacy rows with plan_hash=None are never repaired, but the code comments reveal this is a deliberate design choice to avoid mislabeling — the concern is valid but the tradeoff is intentional and documented. Amendment fr-5-39bc594e correctly identifies that the round-trip tests are example-based rather than structural and would not catch drift from new optional fields.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-5-f1c7b7b6","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies a gap: pre-existing TaskRunEntry rows with plan_hash=None are never backfilled from the snapshot, even during finalization. The code comments at lines 2927-2931 and 3257-3261 explain the rationale (avoiding mislabeling a v1 attempt as v2 when snapshot.plan_hash advances), but this logic conflates two distinct cases: (1) the snapshot hash has genuinely advanced past the attempt's plan version (mislabel risk — legitimate concern), and (2) the row was simply created before auto-population existed and the snapshot hash has NOT changed (repair opportunity — currently missed). A legacy row that started under the same plan version the snapshot still holds could safely be backfilled, but the current blanket prohibition prevents this. The result is that Issue 3 is only fixed going forward for new rows, not for repairing legacy data. This is a real defect in the repair path."},{"amendment_id":"fr-5-39bc594e","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that the drift-detection tests at lines 3768-3812 are example-based round-trips rather than structural guards. Both tests populate ALL fields with Some values and verify the round-trip succeeds, but they cannot detect a new optional field added to the model's render function (StartJournalDetailsPayload or CompletionJournalDetailsPayload) that is absent from the fs adapter's parsing struct. Because the fs structs use `deny_unknown_fields`, a NEW field in the model would cause the parse to fail at runtime — but the test wouldn't catch it at compile time or even at test time unless a test case happens to exercise that field. Worse, if the model adds a field with `skip_serializing_if = Option::is_none` and it defaults to None, the round-trip test passes perfectly because the field is never serialized. The amendment's ask — structural/compile-time drift detection rather than example-based — remains unaddressed. The duplicated schema in fs.rs is a real maintenance hazard."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"3f2fd4d0-743e-4915-ab41-11690e068d85"}
